One thing can be said with certainty: these new trends will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions are in part discrediting the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have enacted laws since 2009 that make it more difficult to register or vote.
This was a new development after the November 2010 elections, which brought 675 new seats to the Republicans in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills limiting voting rights in 41 states were passed in 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require an elector to submit a photo identity card and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register the elector on the day of the will, and remove the right to vote from citizens who have a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to submit an identity card with a picture.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Act in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated legislation to require voters to submit photo identity cards in 34 states.
It is important to note that, unlike Québec, American citizens do not have as universal an identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people who have reached the age to vote, do not have an identity card with a picture issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
The cost of obtaining the required identity card is often over $100.
New constraints disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 years of age, and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo identity.
But that's not all.
Students who are considered to vote for Democrats are not allowed in several states to use a photo identity card issued by their educational institution.
At the same time, the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for the Republicans, to use the licenses issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of American citizenship to vote.
For the first time, such a request was made in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than 10 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are US citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latin Americans.
It is believed that two thirds of Latin American voters vote in favour of the Democratic Party.
In addition, the Republican legislature initiated laws in 2011 to abolish voter registration on the day of the vote in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wished to register.
This limit has not passed without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to put about 10 million citizens on the list.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent drop in the voter registration rate in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have enacted laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period of early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33 per cent of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although the latter represented only 13 per cent of the total number of voters in the state.
The same was true of Latin Americans.
In their representation of only 11 per cent of the electorate, they represented 24 per cent of the citizens who voted ahead.
In contrast to the whites, who make up 76 per cent of the voters, only 46 per cent of the voters voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws limiting voter registration.
A number of draft laws have been enacted by the Democratic Governors.
The most controversial laws have been suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney-General.
This has made it possible to limit the negative effects in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have enacted laws requiring photo identity.
However, the new rules that have come into effect will certainly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Democratic critics denounce the bias of laws that have been adopted, with a clear focus on influencing the 2012 elections in key states.
The report of the Brennan Center of 2011 shows that the states that passed the laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Bench to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions are in part discrediting the system of American democracy.
