In the past summer, the report that scientists may have been able to locate Higgs' boson has caused real anxiety - and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much.
And it's also the last part, the existence of which was predicted in the Standard Model -- our best, or, in any case, "the least imperfect" description of the nature and behavior of matter -- but that was never found in the past.
But physicists don't really think it's Higgs' boson.
We know, without a shadow of doubt, that we're dealing with a real new particle, and that it's very much like the Higgs Boson, as the Standard Model predicted.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical convention in Kyoto seem to support this, although some data are not yet available for full confidence.
Let's still think of this as Higgs boson, because the chances of error seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law is absolutely inevitable, saying that two things can't end up in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to get past this rule, don't even try too hard, or you're gonna hurt yourself.
But while Particle Physics is a rather bizarre world, it turns out that it also has one such law: the principle of excluding Paulie, which posits that two particles cannot take the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is, in general, in some of their characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens, called ferrions, who wisely follow the principle of Paulie.
In the other, the bosons, an abominable gang of anarchists, who have no respect for anything - at least this principle, which means that they can find themselves in the same place at the same time.
According to the website (such as the most unusual) particle Adventure of Berkeley Labs, these bosons are in turn divided into two groups: the mesomons we're not talking about, and the "partikels of power" through which the main forces of nature are being spread, and which in some way include the Higgs Boson.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all as exotic as you might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronology, it's thanks to one incredibly trivial boson, a photon, or "part of the light," which is the "courier" of an electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "breaks" an electromagnetic field in this particular place, about as a stone thrown into the pond.
From this “violation” is a electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) and this wave is nothing but a photon, and therefore one of the “power carriers”.
A more stable field
The same thing happens with Higgs' boson, with the difference, that in order for this boson to come up, it's got to be "breaking" another field, the Higgs field.
But the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to energize it, you have to get very, very high energy, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only shake a very big stone.
That's why we need a massive particle accelerator, like the one that's being used in CERN, the Great Adronic Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! - to achieve such immense energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful in explaining the relationship between Higgs' boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others don't: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on to the fridge.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have a mass, while others (like photon, by the way) do not.
