The last one, I must say, still has significant shortcomings, without suggesting any explanation for the gravity (ah!) or for the dark matter that shapes about 80 percent of the universe (oh-oh!).
But so far, the CERN has not found such differences.
Effect
The use of these studies for the daily life of an average man is more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
Look, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research at Bella's labs couldn't even imagine what revolution their work would cause.
They foresaw their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist, Willard Boyle, who was working at Bell Labs, where a laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previously impulsive) in 1962, said that the laser was initially viewed as a more "labular gadget."
