There's no way out.
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for not complying with their request after the palliative care team has eased their pain.
It should be noted, however, that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the fight against pain.
Elsie Monroe, the director of palliative care at the Grand Montréal House, said that the patients are not sensitive to pain in 8% of the cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to a palliative session in which the patient sleeps until he dies, either from time to time or permanently.
We can't pretend we don't know about this suffering any more.
Increasingly, patients who are unable to relieve the pain will be able to access a palliative session.
Patients with pain always say the same thing, "I want to die."
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want to get euthanasia," it means "I want to get better."
