Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of European Space Agency ministers, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has been active in a number of Agency projects in the following years.
But Poland's way to space has been much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts used to fly to space, but that was not always the case.
I would like to recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who, on 6 December 1933, presented ideas to the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory from his pioneering work "Introduction to Space."
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, and after a few years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and Andre Luis Hirsch award for "Introduction to Space."
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), quoted above, later became a great propagator of astronomy and space.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and has written a number of books on these sciences.
Gadomsky has become a well-known world space propagandist, and his contribution has been appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the back of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a rail train was built in Poland with a missile engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea was not known, nor was the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket was to be used to break up the cart or to stop it.
Information about this is only available from the press of that era.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to think about the rockets.
The study was carried out by the Armament Engineering Section in cooperation with Professors Mélislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokjitski.
The remaining material shows that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the German troops coming, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the Specialized Press introduced the idea of a photovoltaic fighter missile, which was proposed by the Rogozinski engineer, and the following year, the work of the author, Lelili-Kivoblocski, was carried out by an air-toped and air-bombed missile.
Both projects have been developed for the military use of missile engines.
Prior to the war, all the missile-use projects were run by the Tymczasawy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy, which coordinated all the work.
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work was completed due to the outbreak of the war.
The next scientific work on space has appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polkie Towarzystwo Astronomyczne).
For the first time, there is a reference to society in the November 1954 issue of the Journal of Problems, which publishes four voluminous articles on Astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich offered to organize a space society.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were already on the move, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PAA) has tried to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and it has become a real member in the fall.
And the following year, the first Chairman of the PAA, Cazirez Zarankewicz (1902-1959) became Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful Meteorological Missile RM (Raquieta Meteorologiczna), which was the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first was launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, which was able to cross a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested on the Bledovsk Desert.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already in a position to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could have crossed 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was put on hold.
The origin of the first RM-type missiles was a Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed to be two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed, which differ in size for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A missile had a space of 0.4 litre, Meteor-1B a space of 0.34 litre, and Meteor-1C a space of 0.62l.
The maximum range for all three types of flight was 37 km.
In the period between 1965 and 1968, a Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight test began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile with a 380 kg start-up weight was able to produce a useful 10 kg load up to a height of about 60 km.
The versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland ' s joining COSPAR (Space Research Committee) in 1960 and the creation of a COSPAR national committee two years later.
In addition, under the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermashzewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
