Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
In the view of Stephen Sabo, an expert in the US-Europe connection, in doing so, Berlin is on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany must now be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to show its independence, without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote to impose a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO made this proposal.
Is it hard for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is, it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, moving from the policy that the US was, so to speak, to the very German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are back between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not accustomed to it.
I think they're just finding out what they're doing, but they're on the way to a more normal foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy that France or the United Kingdom has pursued.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy from a German point of view mean?
It is a willingness to take a national stand independent of the position of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is dependent on economic policy, that is, export and links to certain regions, such as Russia, China, or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests differ to a large extent from those of other major States, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Did these economic interests have an impact on the position in the Middle East conflict and on the United Nations vote?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, in particular in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to offend the public and the elite in the Arab countries.
In any event, it has a role to play.
But I wouldn't give it too much meaning, it's not a complete one-sided connection.
But in any event, it's an important part of the Germans' calculations.
Has Germany harmed its relationship with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the US, there is a prevailing understanding of the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as it was in the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
Indeed, it signalled that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
On the contrary, the United States has made clear its support for the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the US and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama Government, in its heart, has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But in view of the local political situation, the Government, of course, cannot take this position outright.
I believe that the fundamental differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
