The U.S. Army has been charged with theft of thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, who was accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, had not availed himself of a lot of opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said he had been put on hold in a military prison.
During cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mede, Maryland, the Military Prosecutor, Major Ashden Feyn, stated that the records of the weekly visits to Manning by the prison authorities for nine months in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain any complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the Defence motion to discontinue Manning ' s case, on the basis that the conditions of his detention were brutal and in themselves a sufficient punishment, was carried out the day after Manning stated that he had been in custody and had intended to commit suicide.
The Military Intelligence Analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is charged with theft of several thousand secret documents while in Iraq.
The material was later published on the WikiLeaks Web site.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the Friday hearing, Prosecutor Fain, together with Manning, reviewed the reports that had been completed after Manning ' s visits to the administration during his stay in Quantico prison, where he was in strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, the prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When D.A. Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he viewed the application of the prison administration as “excellent” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized”.
The reports reviewed do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Pheine argues.
Manning replied that he had expressed his oral concern about the problems and that the officials who had visited had discussed the problems with him and had stated that they would do so, but had not recorded it in writing.
"They've been recording "no problem" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in a conversation," Manning says.
The Military Judge, Colonel Denise Lindh, also asked Manning why he had not complained of the ill-treatment he had received in January 2011 during a meeting of a commission considering the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that session, he wanted to be removed from the “injury warning” regime and eased the conditions of detention.
The military authorities explained that the restricted regime of detention, at a level lower than the surveillance regime for the prevention of suicide, had been put in place to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know I'm okay with them to end the injury prevention regime... so that my standard of living would improve, from my point of view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified to his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had the idea of a suicide in Kuwait, and that one day he had lost consciousness due to the heat.
He explained that it's very psychologically hard when you don't get to know how your fate is handled, and what's going on in the outside world.
