In response to the judge ' s questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard ' s order that he should leave a blanket to cover for, but admitted that no one had ordered him to leave.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked last night because he was trying to show an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer he could have used a slipper or a slipper to hurt himself, but he didn't do it.
That night, according to Manning's statement, his underwear, his slippers, and his sunglasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had to endure during his detention, and would substantially shorten the sentence if Manning was found guilty by a military court, which was to start his trial early next year.
The defence stated that it was planning to invite Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes, while the other charges were to be challenged as superfluous.
The re-opening of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon states that Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of persons under the strictest conditions.
The charges brought against Manning include aiding an adversary, illegal promotion of the Internet, the transfer of information on national defence, and the theft of State property or documents.
