Old Wars in the New Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas faction can be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed has led to the conclusion that such hopes are in vain.
It has become a common, pointless argument about who began; a host of buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, the majority of whom were civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time in the conflict, rockets from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of the capital of Israel, Tel-Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But despite the hopeless links between Israelis and Palestinians in their perpetual conflict, the Middle East has been reshaped.
This can be viewed in a different way, but the events of the Arab Spring have swirled in a mutiny storm with many well-established realities, and the Palestinians and the Israelis have not been able to stay away from the whirlwind that has shaken the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloodthirsty than ever before.
There are, however, reasons for hope of overcoming this fatal impasse.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the cease-fire, which was signed on 21 November, is being implemented, the fighting this week has only reinforced the positions of the militants on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will claim to have forced Israel to retreat despite the loss they have suffered.
Despite the fact that some faction leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million people have been blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled parts of the world, Israel has not been able to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, the leaders of Hamas may well come to the conclusion that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements grows in the Arab world, Hamas has new powerful and rich friends.
The renaissance of the regional leader of Turkey, who once was Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, has been supporting Hamas; her example has been followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic States in the Persian Gulf.
The glorified supporters of Hamas have claimed the creation of an Islamist semi-month around Israel, from Lebanon to the north, in which the warring Hezbollah is operating, to Syria, where the increasingly pro-Islamic rebels are about to overthrow Bashar Assad’s power, and further to Jordan, where the king’s authorities threaten Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region has taken place on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country, Egypt, where the Muslim Brotherhood has been strengthened under President Mohammed Mursi.
Hosni Mubarak, who had ruled Egypt for 30 years and was demolished in 2011, was a secular dictator with little focus on the support of Hamas.
The Muslim brothers, on the other hand, are an organization much like Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas can become a meaningful player whose voice will not be stifled even by Israel and America.
At the same time, the hardline in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli anti-missile system, the Iron Dome, has justified the cost of its creation and has successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israelis can sleep quietly, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained steadfast; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for launching the last round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel ' s economic prosperity, especially under the Government of Binyamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that, since 2004, some 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has been able to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part through the wall that enters the West Bank of the Jordan River, a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and to protect the Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party, in preparation for the 22 January elections, has joined with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What's the point of permissing the Palestinians and giving them a State of their own?
If they hand over all the authority in the West Bank, wouldn't they start launching rockets from there towards Israel, as their brothers do in the Gaza Strip?
It's best to keep them out of the wall and stifle any attempt to lift their heads.
Proponents of the hardline may win; however, their calculations can be disproved in the Arab spring.
While Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defensive part of Israel's budget is greater than all of its Arab neighbours combined.
The outbreak of war with a regional super-Power is not likely to help Arab Governments to strengthen their economies.
The pragmatism of the President of Egypt, Mursi, who worked with Barack Obama on a cease-fire is a good sign and can mark the beginning of a change.
Israel, to the same extent, must bear in mind the long-term consequences of its policies.
As the democratic changes in the Arab countries erupted, depriving the Palestinians of the right to self-determination was a time bomb that would eventually explode in the occupied territories of Israel, like a bus that had been blown up in Tel-Aviv this week.
Repressions are already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic dimension, the growth of the Arab population, is only exacerbating these problems.
The bloodthirsty operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to be paid by the international community ' s growing discontent.
Both sides need an external impulse.
The only solution that is unrelentingly called for by sound representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our paper, is the formation of two States and Israel ' s transfer of territories in return for security.
The hope remains, not too strong in the short term, that a cease-fire will enable other countries to have a more effective impact on the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which has a long time to make a decision to cut off arms to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, has a more lucrative position than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the boundaries of the Jewish State adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the shared use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
That would do more for the creation of a Palestinian State than the upcoming United Nations vote, which could result in a recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
In his first term, he still failed to submit his own peace plan.
Upon his return to the White House, he continued to show a reluctance to join the problem.
This is a catastrophic short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the event of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
The Unified Packing Act for Cigarettes has entered into force in Australia.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and the images of sick body parts are contrasted with the depressing green boxes, which are the same for all cigarette stamps.
The first Australian law on the same-type packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products has come into force in the world, replacing the logos and colored design of the various stamps with a box of depressing olyfolk with depressing images of sick body parts and images of children whose health is affected by the smoking of their parents.
In addition to the various images and inscriptions that warn of the harm of smoking, the only difference between packs that are mandatory from this Saturday is stamp names, which are printed in the same small font.
