There are people for whom their work is hell, and others are literally working in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living from a sulfur mine in the island of Kawah Ijen, in the eastern part of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto goes down to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfurous gas from the depths of the Earth freezes in contact with the air.
He puts the large pieces of sulfur up to 70 kg in two bamboo baskets, puts the baskets on his shoulders, and carries them up on a rocky road.
Up to the top of a volcano of 2,386 meters, it is only 250 meters, but it takes the exhausted porters for more than 40 minutes to climb up with a turtle step, with difficulty to keep the balance and tore the road down carefully so as not to fall or fall off a cliff.
They know that one wrong move can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the rocks of Kawah Ijen a few years ago.
The miners from Cavah Ijen make five eurocents for every kg of sulphur they produce.
Upstairs, they lay the road between the tourists who photographed them, as if they were circus apes and, with their heavy baskets up to three kilometers to the balance that the mining company has set up a bit higher, at a height of 1,850 meters.
This is the PT Candy Ngrimby, a company that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, best and best not to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for Rs. 10,000 (83 Eurocents) to petrochemical production, for this mineral is common in daily life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Because the norm is 70 kg, we make about Rs. 46,000 (Euro3.8) for every move," explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily transfers.
He spends three hours on each one of them, and at the end of the day he feels crushed, but they allow him to save Rs. 138,000 (Euro1.5) by the end of the day.
Although it seems a miser for such an unhuman effort, it is three times as much as he would have made in the field.
“The daily wage for miners is very high in local terms, where the price of the coffee is Rs. 15,000 (Euro1.2) per day, and the average monthly wage is Rs. 2 million (Euro167),” explains a porter who used to work as a rocker on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was Rs. 75,000 (Euro6.2) per day and the plot was not as heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Bnuwanga, a town near the volcano, for a reason that in Indonesia is as devastating as the sera: "I married a girl from Bali, where there are Hindus, and brought her to Java to accept Islam."
Anto asthma, he's breathing hard, coughing all the time, and he's gonna get his eyes up because of the toxic gas.
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kavah Igen, whose sulfur has already begun to affect him, despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He's got asthma, he's breathing hard, he's coughing all the time, and he's gonna get his eyes up because of the toxic gases that emit the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to make his dream come true.
"I'll work for another two years, 'cause I want to open a shop or study a Spanish or a French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punited by life, this sweet and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, a waiter, or a hotel porter, but instead he's doing a mule job.
The deluxe of a filthy wooden hut with other porters, it wakes up every day at 2:00 a.m., because the sulfur never stops running out at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glitters in the middle of the darkness.
Calling out the shadows, Anto goes down to the crater, lighting his way with a small light, connected to his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
Some 400 porters are carrying baskets of grey on their shoulders from the bottom of a volcano.
Despite the high returns, the mining company has not mechanized the production of sulfur to save the cost, nor has it provided any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such hardships.
In fact, they do not even receive a part of Rs. 30,000 (Euro2.5) of the photography fee, which, together with an entry card for Rs. 15,000 (Euro1.2), the guards of this reserve are charging tourists to take a picture of the volcano and its mullel men.
“This is a work for livestock, not for humans,” states Badrusin, a 42-year-old root porter who has spent three decades in Cavah Ijen since he left college.
He's able to raise to 110 kilos, and he says he's going to be able to take the job "as long as he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children between the ages of 18 and 10.
If I don't retire, I'm gonna die here, 'cause a volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes, when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in dense columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so patient that no one complains of their severe diseases... more serious, apparently than their common problems with breath, arthrosis, knee pains and ulcers on their shoulders, which have been deformed under the weight of the basket.
By balancing the basket on his back, the Unainik can now only raise 50 pounds in his 53 ’ s.
Every day, he and his companions take 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks are transporting to a warehouse in Tamansari, traveling 18 km on a narrow path in the woods.
"I'm not gonna retire, I'm gonna die here, 'cause a volcano is my whole life," says Unaignicus, wide opening his mouth with a few teeth short.
Of his five children, an older man, 30 years old, he also works as a sulfur vector.
Time is running out, but poverty permeates one of the hardest things in the world: what human mules do from Kawah Ijena.
