UNASUR summit ends without the declaration of Lima
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the declaration of the Lima Declaration, which was previously and in theory signed by the seven bound participants.
Efe has tried to access the document signed at the Sixth Assembly of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR on a number of occasions, but sources from the Office and the President ' s Administration have indicated on the main page that it will be translated after the closure, but have then confirmed that it will be published on the Peru Government ' s website at a certain time.
On questions about the text, they indicated that the content had been given by the President of Peru, Oliant Umala, during the press briefs.
The access of journalists to information about the Summit has been restricted all the time.
In the course of the day, it was only aired in the press hall, a video of the President's Assembly with a message of "closed session, no sound. "
Not much of the information that was circulating among reporters was shared by some UNASUR government press representatives who attended the meeting, but not Peruan.
The only document distributed in the course of the day was a list of participating presidents, which caused discontent on the part of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
The Government of the President of Peru subsequently sent an e-mail to the media with a "final declaration" of the summit, but this is a message from Umala, rather than an official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was also not distributed, despite press insistence.
The ASPA official website can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities had made efforts to ensure that the system of transmission for all journalists was in place, but to limit the information to the extent possible.
The summit also culminated in a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt a judgement of the Hague Court, which settles a territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Pinier, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice, which began on Monday in The Hague the hearing of the statements of both parties, in the context of the charge that Lima had put forward against Santiago.
"We will respect and implement a decision that will make clear the differences we are currently representing in this international court," said Umala, next to her Chilean colleague.
“Chili was, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of differences, covenants, and international tribunals,” he added, and applauded Umal's hand in the context of the two flags.
The confirmation by the two Presidents that they would be subject to the International Court of Justice took place immediately after Colombia protested this week against the Bogotá Pact, according to which it recognized subjection to the verdicts of the international court following the decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it found to be wrong.
The summit was held in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rusef; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former President, Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Umala, was responsible for the opening of the debate in the morning and for the closing of the summit, just after noon in Lima time.
The Head of State read the outcome document, in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and action lines had been approved for 31 South American projects, and that the expected investment amounted to $17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would take “important steps towards the purpose of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the residence agreements”.
He reported that action was being taken to improve “cooperation in the fight against public insecurity and organized transnational crime, action to increase the availability of drugs, low-cost Internet access in all parts of South America, and to take into account the combined and effective risk of natural disasters”.
Since Europe is in crisis, “the economic unification (Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our productive base and foresaw a better future for our cities,” Oomala added.
"We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve South America's connectivity, especially in the countryside and border zones ... uniting our countries and creating new economic schemes," the Peruvian President said in a message he read.
Among the projects, he mentioned that five were from Peru, and were restricted to transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, while two focused on a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide any more details.
The outcome document also addressed the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to re-accede to the Union of South American Nations, from which it is now excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united and to have good relations among its neighbours, was another theme highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before he began to attend the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet with his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City, to negotiate in a respectful manner the maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of an international court challenged by Bogotá.
"The next day (saturday), perhaps meet President Daniel Ortega," said Santos.
“Let us renegotiate all these paths; they are not mutually exclusive, including a pact with Nicaragua, will require discussion with Nicaragua”, he stressed.
"with President Ortega, I hope I can tell him we can deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," he added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they have a new President, Henrique Peña Nieto, to take office.
Also in the context of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc met in advance to adopt the 2013 Action Plan, which is aimed at strengthening dialogue and consensus on the protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the participation of the last country has been suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
